article.description: Chante Black scored 15 points and Duke beat Boston College 69-58 on Monday night.
article.headline: Black nets 15 points as Duke never trails vs. BC
article.linkText: Black, No. 6 Duke hold down Boston College
article.story:
DURHAM, N.C. -- Duke wouldn't let another late lead slip away again.

Chante Black scored 15 points and Duke (No. 6 ESPN/USA Today, No. 4 AP) held on to beat Boston College 69-58 on Monday night.

After blowing a six-point lead in their first Atlantic Coast Conference loss to Florida State last Thursday, the Blue Devils responded against Boston College.

In the 82-75 overtime loss to the Seminoles that snapped a 15-game winning streak, the Blue Devils (18-2, 6-1) let a six-point advantage slip in the final 48 seconds of regulation.

On Monday, the Eagles (17-3, 5-2) cut an 18-point deficit down to six on three occasions late in the second half.

This time the Blue Devils had a strong response, and jumped back into a tie for first place in the ACC thanks to Florida State's 72-71 loss to Maryland also on Monday.

"We've finished a lot of games, a lot of hard games," Duke coach Joanne P. McCallie said. "So I think [it was] more about just focusing and executing what we do and staying in the moment."

Carrem Gay scored 14 points and Joy Cheek had 10 for the Blue Devils, who rediscovered their usually stellar defense in the first half.

Duke allows opponents to shoot just 33 percent second best in the nation. But in the loss to the Seminoles, Florida State shot 46 percent the best percentage an opponent has hit against Duke. The 82 points marked the second-highest total against the Blue Devils this season.

On Monday, Duke forced 15 of Boston College's 23 miscues in the first 20 minutes -- and scored 16 points off of them -- to grab a seemingly secure 37-21 halftime advantage. While the Eagles shots 43.1 percent for the game, they hit just 37 percent of their shots in the first half.

The Blue Devils got their hands in passing lanes, contested almost every field-goal attempt and blocked shots when the Eagles had fast-break opportunities.

"I thought in the first half we looked scared," Boston College coach Sylvia Crawley said. "It took almost the whole half to settle down and play hard."

That's exactly what the Eagles did after halftime, when Mickel Picco scored 13 of her game-high 18 points.

With the sharp-shooting Picco hitting an array of midrange jumpers and Duke turning the ball over 12 times in the second half, Boston College put the pressure on the home team to pull out its 11th consecutive game at Cameron Indoor Stadium and avoid losing back-to-back ACC games for the first time since the 1999-2000 season.

Abby Waner made a 3-pointer to give Duke a 65-56 lead with less than 2 minutes remaining and Boston College didn't get closer than seven from there, giving the Blue Devils their sixth consecutive win over the Eagles.

"We really just want to put teams away," Black said. "Even after this game, everybody's hungry to really have a game where we actually dominate all the way through."

Duke dominated for a half, holding the Eagles scoreless on nine consecutive possessions to turn a 14-9 lead into a 21-9 advantage.

When Boston College got within 28-19, Duke scored nine straight points sparked by two fast-break layups to grab a commanding 37-19 lead. The Blue Devils flustered the Eagles with a full-court trap and had a bigger player on the 5-foot-7 Picco at almost all times.

"One of the things we really focused on was trying to be more physical and keeping contact with shooters because there are always a lot of screens set up for good shooters," said Jasmine Thomas, who had three of Duke's 18 steals.

Waner had a team-high six steals to go with nine points for Duke. Carolyn Swords scored 12 points on 5-of-5 shooting and Ayla Brown added 11 for the Eagles, who had their four-game winning streak snapped.
